ical improvement occurs within 24 hours of gluten elimination","Diagnosis requires detection of IgE anti-gliadin antibodies","Most children present without gastrointestinal symptoms","Small intestinal biopsy shows increased villous height"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECoeliac disease has strong associations with other autoimmune conditions. \u003Cstrong\u003EType 1 diabetes mellitus and autoimmune thyroid disease\u003C/strong\u003E are particularly common comorbidities, occurring in up to 8% and 15% of coeliac patients respectively.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClinical improvement occurs within 24 hours\u003C/strong\u003E - Symptom improvement typically takes weeks to months on a gluten-free diet\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiagnosis requires detection of IgE anti-gliadin antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E - IgA anti-tissue transglutaminase and anti-endomysial antibodies are the diagnostic serological markers\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMost children present without gastrointestinal symptoms\u003C/strong\u003E - The majority present with classical symptoms including chronic diarrhoea, failure to thrive and abdominal distension\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmall intestinal biopsy shows increased villous height\u003C/strong\u003E - Characteristic findings include villous atrophy with crypt hyperplasia\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis requires both positive serology and characteristic histological changes on small intestinal biopsy while consuming gluten.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Coeliac disease is strongly associated with type 1 diabetes mellitus (8%) and autoimmune thyroid disease (15%)","Diagnosis requires positive IgA anti-tissue transglutaminase and anti-endomysial antibodies, not IgE antibodies","Small intestinal biopsy shows characteristic villous atrophy with crypt hyperplasia"],"references":["Bolia R, Safe M, Southwell BR, King SK, Oliver MR. Paediatric constipation for general paediatricians: Review using a case-based and evidence-based approach. J Paediatr Child Health. 2020 Nov;56(11):1708-1718. doi: 10.1111/jpc.14720. PMID: 33197982","Constipation in children and young people: diagnosis and management. London: National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE); 2017 Jul. (NICE Clinical Guidelines, No. 99.) Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK554924/","Pawasarat A, Biank VF. Constipation in Pediatrics: A Clinical Review. Pediatr Ann. 2021 Aug;50(8):e320-e324. doi: 10.3928/19382359-20210714-01. Epub 2021 Aug 1. PMID: 34398719","Sahin Y. Celiac disease in children: A review of the literature. World J Clin Pediatr. 2021 Jul 9;10(4):53-71. doi: 10.5409/wjcp.v10.i4.53. PMID: 34316439; PMCID: PMC8290992."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53986"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15349"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53986"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T20:02:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T20:05:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8040"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68529"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical studen